Wyclif replies that, as regards Euclid's definition ol the angle — the meeting of two lines - this is merely a genetic, notan essential definition. Euclid indeed says what causes an angle; but that is not the angle itsels. As to the rest, the answer is ready: Euclid’s theory con· cerns only sensible angles, not such as are found amongst points which touch; such, lor instance, as form triangles which have sides only two points long, and os which the apex is an angle which cannot be bisected‚ &e - All this cannot be imagined, and should, therefore, be denied from a merely geometrical point ol view (52, 55).
